definition.value: An ortho-fused compound in which at least one of the rings contains at least one heteroatom.
A compound with the general formula R2C=O (R=/=H) where one or more of the R groups contains an oxy (-O-) group.
An oxyketone with the general formula R2C(=O) (R=/=H) where one or more of the R groups contains an oxy (-O-) group and the oxy and carbonyl groups are bonded to the same carbon atom.
An EC 3.2.* (glycosylase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of any glycosidase (i.e. enzymes hydrolysing O- and S-glycosyl compounds, EC 3.2.1.*).

An antiviral drug targeted at influenza viruses. Its mode of action consists of blocking the function of the viral neuraminidase protein (EC 3.2.1.18), thus preventing the virus from budding from the host cell.
An oxoicosatetraenoic acid having a 5-oxo group; and (6E)-, (8Z), (11Z)- and (14Z)-double bonds.
A mixture composed from maneb and zineb, which is used as a broad-spectrum contact fungicide.

A polymeric complex of manganese with the ethylene bis(dithiocarbamate) anionic ligand. An agrochemical fungicide, it is used to control a variety of diseases including blight, leaf spot, rust, downy mildew and scab.

A polymeric complex of zinc with the ethylene bis(dithiocarbamate) anionic ligand. Formerly used as an agricultural fungicide for the control of downy mildews and rusts, its use is no longer permitted in the US or the EU.
A glycolipid and which the glyco component is specified as galactosyl.
An antifungal metabolite of Sordaria araneosa that inhibits protein synthesis. It has a tetracyclic diterpene glycoside structure.
A diterpenoid with a tetracyclic skeleton.
A glycerol ether having at least one alkyl substituent on oxygen.
An acyl derivative of phosphatidic acid whose phosphorus acid component is esterified with an N-(2-hydroxyethyl)pyridinium bisretinoid
The stable isotope of copper with relative atomic mass 62.929601, 69.2 atom percent natural abundance and nuclear spin 3/2.
The parent compounds of the ceramide family, composed of sphingosine having an unspecified fatty acyl group attached to the nitrogen.
An ethanolamine substituted at nitrogen by an acyl group.
A leptomycin having a (2E,10E,12E,16Z,18E)-double bond configuration as well as an ethyl substituent at position 17.

A complex, very long chain, polyunsaturated fatty acid whose core structure comprises 8-oxononadeca-2,10,12,16,18-pentaenoic acid having methyl substituents at positions 3, 5, 7, 9, 11 and 15 and a 3,6-dihydropyran-6-one-2-yl group at position 19.
A drug that blocks the action of proteasomes, cellular complexes that break down proteins.

A monocarboxylic acid that is 4-oxo-1,4-dihydroquinoline-3-carboxylic acid which is substituted on the nitrogen by a cyclopropyl group and at positions 6, 7, and 8 by fluoro, 3-methylpiperazin-1-yl, and methoxy groups, respectively. Gatifloxacin is an antibiotic of the fourth-generation fluoroquinolone family, that like other members of that family, inhibits the bacterial topoisomerase type-II enzymes.
An organic group that consists of a closed ring. It may be a substituent or a skeleton.
A nanoparticle that contains no carbon.
A cationic phosphosphingolipid consisting of sphingosine having a phosphocholine moiety attached to its primary hydroxyl group.
A cyclic macromolecule containing one or more nitrogen atoms in place of carbon either as the divalent group NH for the group CH2 or a single trivalent nitrogen atom for the group CH.
The biological role played by a material entity when bound by a receptor of the adaptive immune system. Specific site on an antigen to which an antibody binds.
A galactose phosphate compound with undefined anomeric stereochemistry having L-configuration and the phosphate group at the 1-position.

An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of lysine at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of lysine by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing lysine residues.
An antagonist at the A2A receptor.
Organonitrogen compounds that are derivatives of isocyanic acid; compounds containing the isocyanate functional group -N=C=O (as opposed to the cyanate group, -O-C#N).
A polymer composed of repeating ethylamine units.
A halophenol in which the halogen atom is bonded to the carbon atom adjacent to the C-OH group.
The amino acid zwitterion formed from 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine by tranfer of a proton from the carboxy group to the amino group. It is the major species at pH 7.3.
A polymer carrying multiple negative charges.
Any fatty acid containing at least one C=C double bond.
A drug that binds to and activates gamma-hydroxybutyric acid receptors.
A macromolecule containing ionic groups.
The all-cis-isomer of a C22 polyunsaturated fatty acid having four double bonds in the 7-, 10-, 13- and 16-positions. One of the most abundant fatty acids in the early human brain.

A topoisomerase inhibitor that inhibits DNA topoisomerase IV, which catalyses ATP-dependent breakage of both strands of DNA, passage of the unbroken strands through the breaks, and rejoining of the broken strands.
An alpha-D-glucoside deoxygenated at C-2 and C-6.
A tetracyclic antibacterial agent derived from neomycin, being a glycoside ester of neamine and neobiosamine C.

A cephalosporin carboxylic acid anion having methoxy, 2-thienylacetamido and carbamoyloxymethyl side-groups, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group of the semisynthetic cephamycin antibiotic cefoxitin.
A cephalosporin carboxylic acid anion having [(5-methyl-1,3,4-thiadiazol-2-yl)sulfanyl]methyl and (1H-tetrazol-1-ylacetyl)amino side-groups, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group of cefazolin.

A cephalosporin carboxylis acid anion having 2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetylamino and [(2-methyl-5,6-dioxo-1,2,5,6-tetrahydro-1,2,4-triazin-3-yl)sulfanyl]methyl side-groups, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group of ceftriaxone.
